    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-05-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-05-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="152"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d152">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.108 Manchuria/43</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 477</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-05-22">May 22,
                            1936</date>.<lb/>[Received June 15]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to enclose a copy of despatch
                    No. 261 of May 12, 1936, from the Consulate General at Mukden, on the subject of
                    native communist armies in Manchuria.<note n="94" xml:id="d152fn94">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Although there have from time to time been reports of communists among the
                    “bandits” of Manchuria, this is the most concrete information yet received in
                    regard to them and their organization. No reports have been received of
                    large-scale encounters between these alleged communist armies and the Japanese
                    military, and it is therefore assumed that if such armies actually exist they
                    have been skillful in avoiding clashes with Japanese military patrols.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Nelson Trusler Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
